As far as them never being able to implement something like this dont kid yourselves, it would be very easy to keep people from the internet, at least people who obey laws. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
However, implementing a foolproof system of licensing and then providing or denying internet access would require a bureaucracy that would dwarf anything you could imagine.  You're talking about a system that is in a large number of businesses, universities, and homes, and which is now an integral part of the economy.<br>
<br>
Good luck to any congresscritter who supports this and expects to get elected again.  Get those Supreme Court justices a lot of rest, they'll need it when everyone who might be remotely affected by this (which would be, ohhh, pretty much EVERYONE) files suit against the constitutionality or legality or [ insert fancy term ] of any attempt to deny internet access based on anything but your ability to pay for it.<br>
<br>
Heck, good luck to any congresscritter who expects to see another penny in contributions from any organization that would be adversely affected by this (which would be, ohhh, pretty much EVERYONE).  I'm sure ISPs would love having the government tell them to shut off service to 75% of their users and &quot;not worry&quot; about the staggering loss of revenue.<br>
<br>
It isn't always simply about writing a law or flipping a switch.  It's about knowing when you'd get your ass kicked eight ways to sunday by an angry constituency.  There's no way something like this gets implemented at this point in time.<br>
